##Lianping: 'One size fits all' for China's economy

“

Lianping, chief economist of Zhixin Investment and Chairman of the Forum of Chief Economists of China, said that the continued collapse of the stock markets in Europe and the United States has shown very strong signs of a crisis, and the risk of a global financial crisis is growing. He believes that the domestic real estate policy to "change with the Times" , the real implementation of "city-based policy" , can not mechanically adjust the real estate policy to take the old road of real estate stimulus.

”

Fears of a new global financial crisis have been rising as global financial markets have been shaken by the spread of the new pneumonia outbreak overseas. With the Fed cutting interest rates twice in a rare half-month period, voices are growing louder about how China's macro policy should be applied.

Lianping, chief economist of Zhixin Investment and Chairman of the Forum of Chief Economists of China, said that the recent sharp fall in the stock markets of Europe and the United States has shown very strong signs of a crisis, and the risk of a global financial crisis is growing.

Lianping points to the indiscriminate sell off as a sign that the market has become so panicked that everyone is holding on to their money. It is likely to develop into a pre-condition for a financial crisis -- a condition in which liquidity quickly dries up, causing various debts to be unpayable and ultimately leaving the market in a state of disarray.

"The next step is to see if there is a large number of failures, even of systemically important financial institutions, which would be a very clear signal of a financial crisis, " he said.

Lianping said a small "V" rebound in the Chinese economy was highly likely as the country's new crown disease situation eased. But now that the epidemic is spreading overseas, a global economic slowdown and a recession in some countries may be unavoidable, which could hamper China's efforts to return to normal economic growth, this requires the regulatory authorities to take some targeted measures according to the actual situation and adjust some targets appropriately.

He mentioned that the real estate policy should "change with the Times" , truly implement the "city-specific policies" , can not mechanically adjust the real estate policy as to take the old road of real estate stimulating the economy.

"when it comes to the loosening of property controls [ in some cities ] , maybe some higher-level governments are also worried that people think they are doing it to stimulate the economy and cause a lot of different comments in the market. It's normal to worry, but I think the Seek truth from facts is the soul of policy,"Lianping said.

####Here's a transcript of the interview

In interface news: What do you think of the Fed's renewed emergency interest rate cut and resumption of quantitative easing this week?

Lianping: The big picture is what the market expected, but it's coming in a little bit faster than the market expected. The current market reaction has shown the problem, the market has not been greatly boosted and encouraged, on the contrary, there has been more obvious volatility. I think this is mainly because the market has a lot of doubts about the Fed's further policy space.

In theory, these measures should have some positive effect. The first is to stabilize market confidence, and the second is to inject new energy into the smooth liquidity of the market, which is also very important. For the entire financial system, to maintain the smooth operation of liquidity is essential, otherwise, once the liquidity dried up or phased excessive contraction, will bring about a financial crisis.

But the problem is that in the medium term, if the epidemic develops further and the US economy suffers more negative effects, the economic pressure will increase further. In this case, what else can future policy do? Well, there's some space, but not much.

Interface News: How high do you think the risk of a global financial crisis is this year?

Lianping: The risks are getting bigger. The symptoms of the crisis are not yet fully apparent, but there are very strong signs of a sustained slump like the one in the stock market.

Judging from the US stock market, there have been a number of meltdowns in a very short period of time, which has never happened before, and even during the 2008 financial crisis there were no such fluctuations as there are now. U. S. stock market in the past long-term Bull, in a variety of factors continue to drive, continue to set new highs, increasingly out of the fundamentals. Therefore, this kind of large-scale and deep adjustment will bring a lot of negative impact to all kinds of institutional investors.

In order to deal with such a huge shock, policy really should step in to maintain market stability. But it is a pity that the policy space of the developed countries, especially the United States and some major European countries, is already very limited and there are no more strong policies to deal with. Quantitative easing has been going on for years. If interest rates were cut, where would they be now? Many countries already have negative and zero interest rates.

In this case, the market will feel greater fear of volatility, more uncertain about the future. What will happen to the future market? People think it's a huge risk. So what we've seen is that assets that were supposed to be safe havens, like gold, have also collapsed.

This indiscriminate plunge suggests that the panic has reached such a level that everyone is clutching at their wallets. It is likely to develop into a pre-condition of financial crisis -- a condition in which liquidity dries up in a short period of time, making it impossible to pay off all kinds of debts, and eventually leading to a disorderly state of the market. We need to look further to see whether a large number of financial institutions, or even systemically important financial institutions, are likely to fail, which is a very clear signal of a financial crisis.

Moreover, while it is difficult to draw conclusions about whether the global economy as a whole will slip into recession, the impact of such financial market volatility on the global economy, particularly the outbreak and the fall in oil prices, will be very visible next. Some countries, especially those that are more affected by the epidemic, are more likely to fall into recession in the future, that is, negative economic growth.

Some European economies are more likely to experience negative growth in the coming quarters, and the United States is unlikely to be able to rule it out in the coming quarters. It also casts a wider shadow over the global recession. Of course, there are important economies in the developing world, such as China and India, that might be able to maintain a fairly high rate of positive growth and contribute to the global economy.

Interface News: Since March, the United States has a cumulative rate cut of 1.5 percentage points, this will not force China's central bank to increase the rate cut?

Lianping: There is no pressure to cut interest rates. It's not the same as raising interest rates. If it is to raise interest rates, US interest rates after the rise, or beyond the level of China's interest rates, may cause capital, especially short-term capital outflow, flow to the dollar assets. But now it's the other way around. U.S. interest rates are low, we're higher, so dollar assets don't necessarily attract capital in terms of interest rate differentials, and that doesn't backpedal.

But it does give us room for a further easing of monetary policy. Next, whether we cut interest rates, the key is to see China's own economic needs and policy considerations.

Now, the General Policy Direction is clear. That is, we should intensify counter-cyclical adjustment. Monetary policy should pay more attention to flexibility and moderation. On the other hand, while macro-leverage ratio and the debt level of the enterprise sector are still relatively high, we should not engage in "flooding" and should not extend credit on a large scale. However, the growth rate of credit and social integration has been moderately higher than in previous years, and I think it should be.

Monetary policy as a whole is now a threefold mix of volume, structure and price, and there will be further action in these three areas. The so-called aggregate, that is, liquidity remains reasonably abundant. At present, the interest rates in the money market are low and liquidity is abundant, and there is no big problem. Secondly, structural policies are already being implemented, such as refinancing. Thirdly, price-based policies are also being pushed forward, next may be pushed forward more frequently, that is to say, the future LPR (loan market quote rate) will be significantly larger than last year, LPR, asset-side interest rate cut is likely to be in March.

Interest rate cuts on the debt side could also be a symbolic step forward. Although I am not in favor of the adjustment of the deposit benchmark interest rate, but if the CPI downward trend in the future, the deposit benchmark interest rate appropriately small cut, this possibility can not be ruled out. Of course, taking into account the high level of the CPI stage, I am afraid that there is no room for a substantial rate cut.

Interface News: How do you predict the domestic economy this year?

Lianping: The impact of the epidemic in the country is actually gradually unfolding, especially in January and February, and since March, the situation is gradually improving. If only to see the impact of the domestic epidemic, it should be said that after the two quarters a small "v" rebound is more likely.

But the problem now is that in the process of a v-shaped rebound, it may also be hit by a sharp slowdown in the world economy and recession in some countries, which will pose some obstacles to our future rebound and return to normal economic growth, therefore, in the future, we need to adopt a series of policies in light of the actual economic situation, and at the same time, we should appropriately adjust some of our relevant goals. For example, in the context of achieving basic objectives such as poverty eradication and overall economic growth, could some appropriate adjustments or flexibility be made to some of the relevant policy objectives?

Interface News: What are your expectations for GDP growth this year?

Lianping: I think there is a lot of uncertainty, so can the government give a range for the 2020 growth target? For example, 5.5%-5.8% may be relatively close to changes in real economic performance, and it is possible to achieve this by intensifying counter-cyclical policies.

Of course, we also have to consider the relationship between achieving this goal and maintaining steady job growth. If employment growth is stable, that should be an acceptable growth target. Because employment is ultimately behind economic growth.

Interface News: What are your thoughts on stimulating consumer demand? A lot of people are calling for vouchers for low-income groups. What do you think?

Lianping: to boost consumer demand, there needs to be a balance between fighting the epidemic and pushing consumers in the process of resuming production. For more crowded places, such as food and beverage, the need to do a good job in the prevention and control of the epidemic at the same time, targeted to take some measures to release demand.

As for the consumption coupons, China has a large population and a large population gap. How should they be distributed at different levels? On what scale? Did it work? Is something to think about. If it's a one-size-fits-all, the stimulation may be limited. And for the low-income class, is consumption vouchers bound to increase consumption? That's a problem.

Similar to the 2008"home appliances to the countryside" measures are more effective, because the targeted is stronger. However, after the consumption of rural life has reached a level, the space to do so is relatively small. From the field of home appliances, there are all, from the car point of view, China's car ownership has been very high.

Interface News: What do you think of some of the current proposals for large-scale infrastructure, new infrastructure, and deregulation of Real Estate Policy?

Lianping: under the current circumstances, it is appropriate to make some further adjustments in policy, but at the same time to be more active, but also to grasp the appropriate degree. We do not agree that economic policy can be "flooded" without any bottom line or excessive measures, which will lead to sequelae and create many new problems for the economy afterwards.

There is no doubt that infrastructure, as an important area of investment, should be an important aspect of the future policy role. Because with the world economy under recessionary pressure, it is hard to see exports rising much, if at all, and it is hard to see a very strong short-term move to stabilise the economy in terms of consumption. At the same time, there is a need for infrastructure itself, new urbanization, regional economic integration, and many new areas of the economy that require a range of infrastructure, and we have the fiscal capacity. In this case, the introduction of policy-driven infrastructure construction, including traditional infrastructure and "new infrastructure" , I think it should be the right time, but also to grasp the right degree.

In real estate, I think the main problem is how to "change with the Times" the relevant policies, do not engage in "one-size-fits-all" , the full implementation of "city-specific policy" .

As the so-called "changes with the Times" , in the past few years, due to the greater upward pressure on house prices across the country, most places introduced many policies that restricted demand. The situation has now changed a lot, in many places, there has been a shift from a lot of demand to a lack of demand, and there is downward pressure on prices. This change in demand requires a corresponding change in policy and can not be mechanically interpreted as reusing real estate as a means of stimulating economic growth. In the case of insufficient demand, many cities are still there to engage in the so-called "four limits" , itself is not necessary.

The problem is that under the current system, many places clearly need to make some adjustments, but they are very careful not to do so, looking around for fear of being labeled as "using real estate to stimulate the economy. ". In this respect, I think we should proceed from reality and adjust different cities according to their own actual conditions. Now, the State Council proposed the real estate policy "in line with the city policy" , and has not been fully implemented.

Interface News: a more interesting recent phenomenon is that some places proposed to reduce the down payment ratio, but the front foot just published, the back foot was immediately withdrawn. Is this what you were talking about earlier?

Lianping: This is the one-size-fits-all. In this regard, I think the relevant policies need to be clarified at a higher level. Now to say (some cities) real estate control policy loosening, perhaps some higher-level governments also have concerns, for fear that people do so in order to stimulate the economy, causing many different comments on the market. It's normal to worry, but I think the Seek truth from facts is the soul of policy.

In order to ensure the full implementation of "city-specific policy" , it is necessary to have a reasonable and appropriate evaluation mechanism. For example, some cities proposed real estate policy to change what can be reported assessment, rather than that after the report was "one-size-fits-all. ". We also believe that the demand situation in some cities must have changed significantly and that policies need to be adjusted.
